                    <marginalia_text>
                       = Primus ex plebe Tribunus Militum, Consulari potestate. Post Xviros decem Tribuni militum, qui summa[e] rei pra[e]essent: s[upr]a, 83. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Primus Tribunus militum, consulari" type="straight"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000105" text="83"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The first Military Tribune with consular authority from the people. After the decemvirs there were ten military tribunes, who were to take charge of the most important affairs, [see] above 83.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Mutandi apud populum nunq[uam] deest uel causa, uel causatio. Nec ratio caret appetitu: nec appetitus sua quadam ratione. 
                        Latissimè patet tam sophistica, quàm logica causarum, aliorumq[ue] argumentorum. Nec populus subtiliter; 
                        nec senatus semper graviter ratiocinatur. Pro tempore ferè asseruntur, refellunturq[ue] omnia.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The people never lack a reason or excuse for change. Reason is not without desire, nor is desire without its own kind of reason. 
                Of the causes and other arguments the most amenable is the one that is both cunning and logical. And the people do not argue delicately, 
                nor does the senate always reason impressively. Almost all points are made and refuted to suit the occasion.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
